and you don't know what to expect.

257
00:13:19,717 --> 00:13:21,098
So it creates uncertainty,

258
00:13:21,398 --> 00:13:25,100
but it is also a very sustainable way to create new maps

259
00:13:25,720 --> 00:13:27,101
because you don't have to end craft them.

260
00:13:29,022 --> 00:13:30,363
So our idea was really,

261
00:13:31,224 --> 00:13:34,246
players are gonna have million of different maps,

262
00:13:35,466 --> 00:13:36,147
it's gonna be amazing.

263
00:13:37,871 --> 00:13:41,113
But we found out really quickly that the players

264
00:13:41,253 --> 00:13:43,615
testing our game would really have a feeling that

265
00:13:43,635 --> 00:13:45,156
there's just one map.

266
00:13:47,737 --> 00:13:53,741
The chaos that we put into the random generator was not

267
00:13:53,841 --> 00:13:55,242
appreciated to its fullest.

268
00:13:55,442 --> 00:13:58,324
Like they couldn't really explain where they were or

269
00:13:58,384 --> 00:14:01,266
what the difference was between all the maps or all

270
00:14:01,286 --> 00:14:01,886
the permutation.

271
00:14:03,035 --> 00:14:04,536
So we went back to the drawing board

272
00:14:04,756 --> 00:14:10,159
and found some rules to use to fix this problem.

273
00:14:11,200 --> 00:14:15,563
So first off, we would build about five maps

274
00:14:15,983 --> 00:14:17,544
within each team.

275
00:14:17,624 --> 00:14:19,145
So we created that concept of teams.

276
00:14:19,205 --> 00:14:21,407
So you have here, Macmillan Estate,

277
00:14:21,627 --> 00:14:23,288
Coldwind Farm, Otoeven Wreckers,

278
00:14:23,308 --> 00:14:24,969
the first teams that we created.

279
00:14:25,390 --> 00:14:28,191
They have very different mood and lighting,

280
00:14:28,231 --> 00:14:29,232
so they're recognizable.

281
00:14:30,293 --> 00:14:32,174
Second rule is that every map would be.

282
00:14:32,873 --> 00:14:35,994
would have a specific name and a specific building

283
00:14:36,074 --> 00:14:36,994
that would be static.

284
00:14:37,155 --> 00:14:38,615
So usually found in the middle of the map,

285
00:14:38,655 --> 00:14:39,776
they're really recognizable.

286
00:14:40,316 --> 00:14:43,477
And you know as soon as you see the name of the map

287
00:14:43,637 --> 00:14:45,698
where you are and what to expect on that front.

288
00:14:46,598 --> 00:14:47,799
The other thing that we made sure

289
00:14:47,939 --> 00:14:50,820
is that we use a landmark asset

290
00:14:51,180 --> 00:14:53,501
that were used usually in corner of the map

291
00:14:54,121 --> 00:14:56,322
to be used as navigational point

292
00:14:56,462 --> 00:14:58,643
and also recognizable that you can actually

293
00:14:59,824 --> 00:15:01,124
know where you are and recognize them.

294
00:15:03,657 --> 00:15:07,739
So this fixed our problem and added something really

295
00:15:07,799 --> 00:15:08,260
interesting.

296
00:15:08,380 --> 00:15:11,622
So as soon as the map is loading and you see the name

297
00:15:11,662 --> 00:15:14,783
of the map, the player would be able, even though that

298
00:15:15,003 --> 00:15:17,085
there's a lot of random component, they would be able

299
00:15:17,125 --> 00:15:20,446
to start preparing their strategy because they knew

300
00:15:20,526 --> 00:15:22,908
that something specific would be in there.

301
00:15:24,268 --> 00:15:27,130
Also, the people watching the game could also start

302
00:15:28,164 --> 00:15:30,844
hypothesis of what the player should be doing to win.

303
00:15:31,264 --> 00:15:32,225
So that was really interesting.

304
00:15:32,265 --> 00:15:34,605
We gave the players and the watchers a language

305
00:15:34,945 --> 00:15:37,086
to be able to talk about the experience too.

306
00:15:37,926 --> 00:15:39,387
This awesome thing happened to me

307
00:15:39,467 --> 00:15:41,347
on the second floor of this asylum

308
00:15:42,107 --> 00:15:44,248
is something that couldn't be made before

309
00:15:44,288 --> 00:15:47,269
because the random aspect, there were no anchors.

310
00:15:49,009 --> 00:15:51,510
So lesson learned here is that you need,

311
00:15:51,910 --> 00:15:54,791
well, we needed to create expectation and anchors

312
00:15:54,971 --> 00:15:55,971
in the procedural world.

313
00:15:56,613 --> 00:16:04,160
Going fully random and fully chaotic is not something that is really pleasant or that you will feel good in your game.

314
00:16:07,494 --> 00:16:09,254
Next big component I want to talk about

315
00:16:09,274 --> 00:16:13,275
that we did during production is load out and progression.

316
00:16:13,315 --> 00:16:18,036
So our goal, our intent was to create a lot of,

317
00:16:18,056 --> 00:16:21,257
you know, bulk of items, add-ons, offerings,

318
00:16:21,557 --> 00:16:23,838
and all of these things that you can

319
00:16:24,218 --> 00:16:25,218
customize your character with.

320
00:16:25,958 --> 00:16:28,879
So we had items that gives you secondary reaction

321
00:16:28,899 --> 00:16:30,159
in the game, such as.

322
00:16:30,671 --> 00:16:33,473
a toolkit for example that repairs generator faster,

323
00:16:34,413 --> 00:16:38,236
add-ons, two add-ons to add to these tool to customize them.

324
00:16:39,156 --> 00:16:41,038
Each character would have four perks

325
00:16:41,538 --> 00:16:42,999
that would also change their abilities,

326
00:16:43,399 --> 00:16:45,000
and the offering is the wild card

327
00:16:45,040 --> 00:16:47,922
that actually changes how the match is gonna be played

328
00:16:47,962 --> 00:16:51,464
and how the procedural aspect of the map could be tweaked.

329
00:16:52,425 --> 00:16:55,367
And we thought that the more we would put in the game,

330
00:16:55,927 --> 00:16:58,929
we would allow player to experiment, that would be fun.

331
00:16:58,989 --> 00:16:59,550
So every time.

332
00:16:59,963 --> 00:17:02,484
you go into a match, you put these components,

333
00:17:02,664 --> 00:17:04,265
it changes the map, it adds chaos,

334
00:17:04,405 --> 00:17:07,186
it adds different stories, and it adds uncertainty.

335
00:17:10,448 --> 00:17:13,389
The other thing that we did is this infinite progression

336
00:17:13,429 --> 00:17:14,609
through the blood web.

337
00:17:14,749 --> 00:17:17,771
So this is a procedural skill tree,

338
00:17:18,131 --> 00:17:20,432
and all of the nodes, the component that you can buy

339
00:17:20,492 --> 00:17:22,173
to evolve your character are also.

340
00:17:22,555 --> 00:17:23,956
procedurally chosen.

341
00:17:24,296 --> 00:17:26,757
So you, every time you evolve your character,

342
00:17:26,777 --> 00:17:28,778
you don't know exactly what it's gonna be

343
00:17:28,898 --> 00:17:30,558
and you need to choose how to build your character.

344
00:17:31,079 --> 00:17:34,240
So again, this was to create a near infinite progression

345
00:17:34,280 --> 00:17:35,720
so that players could play for a long time.

346
00:17:37,021 --> 00:17:39,502
The first, really, the big problem that happened,

347
00:17:39,582 --> 00:17:40,702
so at first it was really good.

348
00:17:40,742 --> 00:17:43,163
I mean, it was appreciated that there was a lot of content,

349
00:17:43,203 --> 00:17:46,364
but experimentation stopped quite quickly.

350
00:17:46,384 --> 00:17:48,385
In a competitive game,

351
00:17:49,555 --> 00:17:50,976
players want to win.

352
00:17:51,316 --> 00:17:53,437
So obviously there's gonna be a meta build,

353
00:17:53,737 --> 00:17:57,579
the build that is judged perfect for survivors and killers.

354
00:17:57,979 --> 00:17:59,440
It's gonna be on the web,

355
00:17:59,840 --> 00:18:03,421
and then players will want to have this specific thing.

356
00:18:03,942 --> 00:18:07,203
And our procedural skill tree, the blood web,

357
00:18:07,323 --> 00:18:09,204
would become more frustrating than anything

358
00:18:09,304 --> 00:18:11,745
because you really wanted to be able to achieve

359
00:18:11,805 --> 00:18:12,765
this specific loadout,

360
00:18:12,846 --> 00:18:14,706
and it was really difficult to get there.

361
00:18:17,007 --> 00:18:18,048
Also, it stopped.

362
00:18:18,398 --> 00:18:21,160
completely experimentation, like this is what you would see.

363
00:18:21,781 --> 00:18:24,563
So the way we changed our approach with that now

364
00:18:24,603 --> 00:18:27,366
is that instead of doing bulk of different items

365
00:18:27,446 --> 00:18:28,927
to release when we do an update,

366
00:18:29,328 --> 00:18:32,650
we focus on less things but that are more meaningful

367
00:18:32,931 --> 00:18:35,553
and that shakes the meta so that the players

368
00:18:35,673 --> 00:18:38,436
actually start to experiment and adapt again to a new meta.

369
00:18:40,798 --> 00:18:42,799
Another problem with a bulk of items like that

370
00:18:43,000 --> 00:18:45,862
is that it adds exponential weight on your team.

371
00:18:46,826 --> 00:18:50,592
So an example of this is the moon offering.

372
00:18:50,692 --> 00:18:55,399
So these are a set of four offerings that changes the

373
00:18:55,439 --> 00:18:56,260
lighting of a map.

374
00:18:56,621 --> 00:18:59,064
So you can change the moonlight so that the level is

375
00:18:59,104 --> 00:19:00,266
brighter or darker.

376
00:19:01,187 --> 00:19:04,269
And every time we create a new map,

377
00:19:04,590 --> 00:19:08,332
the artistic team need to do a basic lighting pass

378
00:19:08,532 --> 00:19:10,674
for the normal experience, and then make sure

379
00:19:10,714 --> 00:19:13,376
that the combination of all the different moon offering

380
00:19:13,396 --> 00:19:16,838
that the players can play will have a great lighting too.

381
00:19:17,118 --> 00:19:19,980
And then we also add a perk that would also affect

382
00:19:20,260 --> 00:19:21,921
the lighting of that specific character.

383
00:19:22,001 --> 00:19:24,023
So there's all these permutations to,

384
00:19:25,083 --> 00:19:27,245
it's a lot of work just to have a perfect lighting

385
00:19:27,285 --> 00:19:27,985
for all of these things.

386
00:19:29,178 --> 00:19:34,803
So our solution for that, I mean it was a great gimmick of an idea at first, it was cool,

387
00:19:35,323 --> 00:19:39,126
but since it's not used that much and adds so much problem to the team,

388
00:19:39,267 --> 00:19:41,268
we decided to retire these items.

389
00:19:41,668 --> 00:19:44,771
That's fine too, so they just disappeared, they don't appear on the blood web anymore,

390
00:19:45,371 --> 00:19:47,013
players cannot play them anymore.

391
00:19:50,161 --> 00:19:52,824
So the lesson here is, don't be afraid, be courageous.

392
00:19:53,345 --> 00:19:56,908
You might have released with something awesome,

393
00:19:56,948 --> 00:19:59,932
but the game evolves in a way that you don't need it anymore

394
00:19:59,972 --> 00:20:01,954
and that you should change so that the game

395
00:20:02,134 --> 00:20:03,676
becomes interesting again, and that's fine.

396
00:20:05,781 --> 00:20:08,342
All right, so fast forward to end of production.

397
00:20:10,002 --> 00:20:12,163
We have a great game in our hands.

398
00:20:12,243 --> 00:20:14,104
We know that it's fun to watch, it's fun to play.

399
00:20:14,924 --> 00:20:16,704
But nobody knows about our studio,

400
00:20:16,764 --> 00:20:17,845
nobody knows about our game,

401
00:20:18,205 --> 00:20:22,246
so we started thinking about building a community

402
00:20:22,346 --> 00:20:23,066
and iPlayers.

403
00:20:23,666 --> 00:20:25,427
So I wanna, in this section,

404
00:20:25,487 --> 00:20:27,428
go quickly over the different tools that we use

405
00:20:27,448 --> 00:20:29,988
to get that community built up.

406
00:20:31,623 --> 00:20:33,884
So for us, we started on Steam.

407
00:20:34,164 --> 00:20:35,825
Obviously, this is where we released the game.

408
00:20:36,225 --> 00:20:38,486
So the Steam forum is where we wanted to start

409
00:20:38,746 --> 00:20:40,367
talking with the players.

410
00:20:41,187 --> 00:20:44,529
And at that time, we had a partner, Starbreeze,

411
00:20:45,269 --> 00:20:47,991
who have a game you might know about, Payday 2.

412
00:20:48,711 --> 00:20:50,452
And at that time, they had one of the biggest

413
00:20:50,512 --> 00:20:51,772
community on Steam.

414
00:20:51,952 --> 00:20:54,053
They had about three million members in their community.

415
00:20:54,634 --> 00:20:57,335
So the deal we did with their player is,

416
00:20:57,855 --> 00:20:59,076
come join our community.

417
00:20:59,863 --> 00:21:03,065
and you will unlock three awesome masks in Payday

418
00:21:03,806 --> 00:21:05,006
teamed on Dead by Daylight.

419
00:21:05,787 --> 00:21:08,649
So a lot of players came in the community.

420
00:21:08,729 --> 00:21:11,671
Obviously a lot of them were there for just the free shit,

421
00:21:12,692 --> 00:21:15,714
but we had a way to talk to them.

422
00:21:15,794 --> 00:21:17,615
So now every time we did an announcement

423
00:21:17,715 --> 00:21:21,278
on our community page, they would receive this message.

424
00:21:21,858 --> 00:21:24,060
And quite a few of them were converted.

425
00:21:24,080 --> 00:21:25,521
I mean, they wanted to know more

426
00:21:25,781 --> 00:21:27,842
and started to follow the project.

427
00:21:30,582 --> 00:21:33,263
Another big thing we did is our first event.

428
00:21:34,043 --> 00:21:36,964
We went to PAX to talk about our game.

429
00:21:37,304 --> 00:21:39,885
And this was a first for the company.

430
00:21:40,445 --> 00:21:41,785
We didn't know really what to expect.

431
00:21:41,945 --> 00:21:45,526
We shipped five PCs, and most importantly,

432
00:21:46,526 --> 00:21:49,267
the dev team to go there and talk about the project.

433
00:21:50,187 --> 00:21:54,308
We had a super cool, nondescript black box of boot

434
00:21:55,208 --> 00:21:56,208
with only the title.

435
00:21:56,809 --> 00:22:00,192
And the most important thing was the giant TV screen

436
00:22:00,352 --> 00:22:01,152
all around the booth.

437
00:22:01,933 --> 00:22:03,875
We knew our game was fun to watch,

438
00:22:04,415 --> 00:22:07,118
so players would come here and test the game

439
00:22:07,158 --> 00:22:09,480
and play a real match and then people around

440
00:22:09,520 --> 00:22:12,222
would be able to look at what was happening

441
00:22:12,382 --> 00:22:13,763
and have fun just watching the game.

442
00:22:15,385 --> 00:22:17,947
The first day was selling the game,

443
00:22:17,967 --> 00:22:20,910
you know, one person at a time, super difficult.

444
00:22:22,011 --> 00:22:23,812
But people were intrigued, they were looking around.

445
00:22:24,216 --> 00:22:26,297
It's the second day that was awesome for us

446
00:22:26,337 --> 00:22:30,379
and a revelation really because there was a lot,

447
00:22:30,599 --> 00:22:32,720
a lot of people just packed around the boot

448
00:22:33,220 --> 00:22:35,201
and we didn't need to explain the game anymore.

449
00:22:35,301 --> 00:22:38,343
The crowd was able to explain to newcomers

450
00:22:38,383 --> 00:22:39,663
what was going on.

451
00:22:39,944 --> 00:22:42,885
The concept is easy to grasp and easy to explain

452
00:22:43,245 --> 00:22:46,207
and it's awesome for this kind of events.

453
00:22:47,595 --> 00:22:49,877
And most importantly, at the end of the event,

454
00:22:49,997 --> 00:22:52,539
we had a lot of content creators, streamers, YouTuber,

455
00:22:53,280 --> 00:22:55,242
that came to see us to tell us

456
00:22:55,262 --> 00:22:56,963
that they were hyped about the project.

457
00:22:56,983 --> 00:22:58,705
They couldn't wait to get their hands on it

458
00:22:58,985 --> 00:22:59,886
to be able to stream it.

459
00:23:00,266 --> 00:23:03,349
They understood the power of this product

460
00:23:04,049 --> 00:23:06,351
as a really entertaining game to watch.

461
00:23:08,173 --> 00:23:10,575
It was actually so important, this factor,

462
00:23:10,835 --> 00:23:12,396
that when we came back.

463
00:23:13,069 --> 00:23:15,872
We really had the choice in production before release,

464
00:23:15,932 --> 00:23:17,894
we had the choice to create one extra mode

465
00:23:17,914 --> 00:23:18,734
that we needed to choose.

466
00:23:18,755 --> 00:23:21,817
Do you want to do an offline mode, kill your friend mode,

467
00:23:22,498 --> 00:23:25,281
or the survivor friend, the social group

468
00:23:25,361 --> 00:23:27,323
that you form survivor with your friends?

469
00:23:28,284 --> 00:23:29,785
And we chose kill your friends

470
00:23:30,165 --> 00:23:31,687
because of the content creator.

471
00:23:31,847 --> 00:23:36,231
We wanted to give them a platform that's safe and offline

472
00:23:36,271 --> 00:23:38,013
so that they could create their videos and have fun.

473
00:23:39,087 --> 00:23:40,169
And it served us really well.

474
00:23:40,310 --> 00:23:43,716
I mean, the streamers really pushed visibility on the

475
00:23:43,756 --> 00:23:44,618
beta-lite on release.

476
00:23:47,376 --> 00:23:50,579
Another tool we use is that we started at that time doing

477
00:23:50,939 --> 00:23:53,622
the weekly Devstream, which is something we still do.

478
00:23:54,382 --> 00:23:57,686
We're going to do our 100th episode soon.

479
00:23:59,667 --> 00:24:03,111
And we started to talk with the community on Twitch.

480
00:24:03,151 --> 00:24:06,294
So people would come and interact directly with us

481
00:24:06,814 --> 00:24:08,896
in the Twitch chat to be able to

482
00:24:09,637 --> 00:24:10,597
ask questions about the game.

483
00:24:11,098 --> 00:24:12,640
and we would show them some gameplay,

484
00:24:12,680 --> 00:24:14,402
show them how it works, answer these questions.

485
00:24:16,003 --> 00:24:18,606
And it's at that time that a lot of questions

486
00:24:18,786 --> 00:24:22,551
would come back, and it was clear that we needed,

487
00:24:22,651 --> 00:24:25,394
as a team, to start and take commitment

488
00:24:25,514 --> 00:24:27,336
and do promises for the future of the game.

489
00:24:29,598 --> 00:24:30,479
So it was time for...

490
00:24:31,386 --> 00:24:32,087
big promises.

491
00:24:32,587 --> 00:24:35,951
So doing promises to the community is scary,

492
00:24:36,012 --> 00:24:38,475
but you really need to do it to start building trust

493
00:24:38,555 --> 00:24:39,195
with that community.

494
00:24:39,816 --> 00:24:42,159
And for us, I'm gonna expose you what the three

495
00:24:42,199 --> 00:24:43,420
big promises we did were.

496
00:24:44,221 --> 00:24:46,284
They were quite easy to do because they're a part

497
00:24:46,304 --> 00:24:47,886
of our values as a team.

498
00:24:50,644 --> 00:24:51,285
No pay to win.

499
00:24:51,705 --> 00:24:54,189
It's something that was asked out of our community.

500
00:24:54,209 --> 00:24:57,574
It's something that a lot of them lived in other projects.

501
00:24:58,695 --> 00:25:01,800
And they wanted us to make commitment that there wouldn't

502
00:25:01,820 --> 00:25:02,561
be any pay to win.

503
00:25:02,581 --> 00:25:03,782
And it's something that

504
00:25:05,044 --> 00:25:10,329
I mean, that we've put some systems in the game to make sure that perks, abilities would

505
00:25:10,349 --> 00:25:14,112
be available to everybody, even though we sold DLC.

506
00:25:15,594 --> 00:25:20,138
We actually just announced today that we're adding a new system or a new way to unlock

507
00:25:20,158 --> 00:25:20,979
characters in the game.

508
00:25:21,759 --> 00:25:27,064
So all of our original characters will now be unlockable with playtime.

509
00:25:27,685 --> 00:25:30,908
So that's how we fulfilled this promise.

510
00:25:32,501 --> 00:25:34,022
We actually did pay to lose.

511
00:25:34,282 --> 00:25:38,664
The first DLC we released was a customization pack,

512
00:25:38,964 --> 00:25:41,645
really flashy, themed on the 80s.

513
00:25:42,245 --> 00:25:44,286
And of course, if you're a flashy character

514
00:25:44,466 --> 00:25:45,787
in a game where you need to hide,

515
00:25:46,187 --> 00:25:47,407
it's pay to lose, right?

516
00:25:49,128 --> 00:25:52,050
Our second promise is no fracturing the community,

517
00:25:52,310 --> 00:25:55,271
and how we did this is every map we released

518
00:25:55,531 --> 00:25:57,552
was going to be free and accessible to everybody.

519
00:25:58,372 --> 00:25:59,393
That was super important to us.

520
00:26:00,874 --> 00:26:03,115
And last one, we'll be as generous as we can.

521
00:26:04,877 --> 00:26:10,420
Since the release of the game, there's two full DLC content

522
00:26:10,440 --> 00:26:12,841
drop that we did completely for free, because we

523
00:26:12,901 --> 00:26:13,662
could at that time.

524
00:26:15,383 --> 00:26:15,783
So that's it.

525
00:26:15,863 --> 00:26:19,225
And also some charity case to give back to the community,

526
00:26:19,886 --> 00:26:21,086
something we did with the streamers.

527
00:26:21,126 --> 00:26:25,589
We created specific items for them, and then sold them, and

528
00:26:25,649 --> 00:26:26,610
all the money went to charity.

529
00:26:28,285 --> 00:26:29,566
super appreciated by the community.

530
00:26:30,287 --> 00:26:32,549
So the lesson here is start building your community

531
00:26:32,709 --> 00:26:33,489
as soon as you can.

532
00:26:34,410 --> 00:26:36,071
Be transparent, be available.

533
00:26:37,793 --> 00:26:40,094
You can't wait till the game is out, obviously,

534
00:26:40,174 --> 00:26:41,475
so as soon as you can.

535
00:26:42,957 --> 00:26:45,118
Interacting with them is super valuable.

536
00:26:46,239 --> 00:26:47,420
And if everything is going all right,

537
00:26:47,580 --> 00:26:48,461
you'll have a community.

538
00:26:50,723 --> 00:26:55,905
So for us, we wanted as a team to be really involved

539
00:26:55,945 --> 00:26:56,786
with the community.

540
00:26:57,246 --> 00:27:01,348
We didn't want the company to be the person

541
00:27:01,448 --> 00:27:02,389
interacting with the community.

542
00:27:02,989 --> 00:27:07,211
So all of us on the team, we did go into the forums

543
00:27:07,491 --> 00:27:10,173
and answered directly and interacted with the members

544
00:27:10,213 --> 00:27:12,614
of the community, answering their questions, their concerns,

545
00:27:13,074 --> 00:27:15,115
and having fun with them, creating characters,

546
00:27:15,455 --> 00:27:18,977
talking about the lore, and this was truly amazing.

547
00:27:21,622 --> 00:27:25,065
Since then, we've added or we transformed some people

548
00:27:25,125 --> 00:27:27,226
into dedicated community manager,

549
00:27:28,347 --> 00:27:29,909
because it's a lot of work

550
00:27:29,969 --> 00:27:31,970
and we have to do other things, obviously.

551
00:27:32,831 --> 00:27:34,272
So let's talk a bit about community.

552
00:27:34,312 --> 00:27:35,073
Let's start with the bad.

553
00:27:35,193 --> 00:27:36,254
Let's get this out of the way.

554
00:27:36,574 --> 00:27:39,176
I actually saw a couple of conference this week

555
00:27:39,376 --> 00:27:40,657
about exactly this problem.

556
00:27:40,677 --> 00:27:43,700
It's something that every one of us need to tackle,

557
00:27:43,740 --> 00:27:45,401
especially in the online multiplayer

558
00:27:45,481 --> 00:27:48,584
with subject like killing, like our game.

559
00:27:51,533 --> 00:27:54,155
you're gonna get your personal life invaded.

560
00:27:54,295 --> 00:27:57,859
Like if you have your personal Facebook or Twitter

561
00:27:57,999 --> 00:27:59,000
and you're having fun on there,

562
00:27:59,580 --> 00:28:00,901
fans are gonna find you,

563
00:28:00,921 --> 00:28:02,103
they're gonna ask you questions.

564
00:28:02,983 --> 00:28:04,725
Some of them are really toxic as well.

565
00:28:05,846 --> 00:28:09,189
And it's dangerous to start and work 24-7 really

566
00:28:09,229 --> 00:28:10,450
because you have your phone

567
00:28:10,530 --> 00:28:11,811
and you want to interact with them.

568
00:28:11,831 --> 00:28:15,254
And because the game is worldwide, it never stops.

569
00:28:15,615 --> 00:28:17,016
This is something you need to be careful about.

570
00:28:17,818 --> 00:28:21,360
When toxicity becomes really, really high, some of them, I

571
00:28:22,180 --> 00:28:27,644
mean, will also get to threats targeting you directly.

572
00:28:28,344 --> 00:28:31,386
And my point here is that, I mean, these things, it

573
00:28:31,466 --> 00:28:32,887
shouldn't happen, but they happen.

574
00:28:33,267 --> 00:28:37,049
And you need to be ready to support team members that are

575
00:28:37,069 --> 00:28:40,551
going to live these kind of scenarios so that they feel

576
00:28:40,591 --> 00:28:41,752
supported and protected.

577
00:28:44,150 --> 00:28:48,475
But the good of having community tremendously outweighs the bad.

578
00:28:49,376 --> 00:28:52,260
It's great for motivation, interacting with the community,

579
00:28:53,581 --> 00:28:56,925
seeing what they build, the arts and craft, they write stories,

580
00:28:57,266 --> 00:29:00,029
they contribute, and make the game much better.

581
00:29:01,707 --> 00:29:03,707
I add only one slide to show you the kind of thing

582
00:29:03,747 --> 00:29:04,728
that our community is doing.

583
00:29:04,908 --> 00:29:07,889
They create their own chapters, the Shia Surprise.

584
00:29:07,909 --> 00:29:09,850
It's awesome, I wanna build that eventually.

585
00:29:11,050 --> 00:29:13,311
Tattoos of our main character, it's crazy.

586
00:29:13,471 --> 00:29:14,612
I mean, cosplay obviously.

587
00:29:15,572 --> 00:29:17,533
Videos, I mean, they're all over

588
00:29:17,673 --> 00:29:19,133
and they make the game richer.

589
00:29:21,054 --> 00:29:23,835
Lesson, ear is one of the most important one.

590
00:29:24,055 --> 00:29:26,156
When you release a game that's going to be live,

591
00:29:27,737 --> 00:29:27,917
you...

592
00:29:28,899 --> 00:29:32,361
create a relationship between you and your community.

593
00:29:33,001 --> 00:29:35,523
And you need to give them this ownership.

594
00:29:36,083 --> 00:29:37,364
It's gonna make the game richer.

595
00:29:37,985 --> 00:29:39,146
It's gonna make the game better.

596
00:29:39,426 --> 00:29:42,007
So it's as much as theirs as it is yours.

597
00:29:42,068 --> 00:29:42,888
You should embrace that.

598
00:29:45,350 --> 00:29:48,032
All right, so stage four, we release the game.

599
00:29:48,272 --> 00:29:49,092
We're now live.

600
00:29:49,312 --> 00:29:51,254
We have the biggest team yet.

601
00:29:51,914 --> 00:29:53,255
I wanna talk a bit about the early days,

602
00:29:53,275 --> 00:29:56,077
what we did in the first month.

603
00:29:56,782 --> 00:29:59,163
about on the live operation of the game.

604
00:29:59,723 --> 00:30:03,565
So continuous monitoring, communication with the community,

605
00:30:03,905 --> 00:30:06,106
super important, fixing bugs aggressively,

606
00:30:06,626 --> 00:30:09,287
and starting work on our major updates.

607
00:30:11,414 --> 00:30:15,778
So here is a, it's quite small, it's the first things that we

608
00:30:15,798 --> 00:30:17,240
released during the first month.

609
00:30:18,601 --> 00:30:21,804
So we've listened to the community demands, and one of

610
00:30:21,824 --> 00:30:24,647
the features that was asked the most was the survive with

611
00:30:24,707 --> 00:30:25,408
friends feature.

612
00:30:25,468 --> 00:30:28,251
So that mode that we had to cut before release.

613
00:30:28,651 --> 00:30:30,853
So a way to be able to play with your friends.

614
00:30:32,362 --> 00:30:35,043
So obviously, because it was a top demand,

615
00:30:35,243 --> 00:30:38,844
we wanted to show that we had a commitment to that game

616
00:30:38,924 --> 00:30:41,185
and to them, so we started working on that.

617
00:30:42,305 --> 00:30:44,266
Other thing we did is that we monitored

618
00:30:44,666 --> 00:30:46,427
the different languages in the community,

619
00:30:46,847 --> 00:30:50,168
and we found out that we had a big community in China

620
00:30:50,348 --> 00:30:51,688
and a big one in Russia as well,

621
00:30:52,348 --> 00:30:54,869
but they didn't have their language supported in the game.

622
00:30:55,749 --> 00:30:57,890
So they had to deal with English.

623
00:31:00,965 --> 00:31:03,367
we added these language in the first month as well,

624
00:31:03,407 --> 00:31:05,007
which was really, really appreciated.

625
00:31:06,228 --> 00:31:09,610
We also released free content, maps, outfits,

626
00:31:09,870 --> 00:31:11,551
just to show that these are the type of things

627
00:31:11,571 --> 00:31:14,292
that we would give away, and again,

628
00:31:14,352 --> 00:31:16,373
to show commitment that we would support this game.

629
00:31:19,335 --> 00:31:20,975
It's not because your community is asking

630
00:31:21,416 --> 00:31:23,397
to change a game that you should do everything, though.

631
00:31:24,077 --> 00:31:26,178
There are some small rules that we kept

632
00:31:26,218 --> 00:31:27,299
that we never touch.

633
00:31:27,839 --> 00:31:29,860
I just want to do the first two example.

634
00:31:31,499 --> 00:31:38,844
I think that since release, every single day, someone asks for voice in the game.

635
00:31:39,164 --> 00:31:42,467
I want to be able to talk to other players.

636
00:31:42,487 --> 00:31:45,489
I want to be able to scream in the game with a mic.

637
00:31:46,329 --> 00:31:51,152
And for us, we knew that this would break completely the immersion, so we've always

638
00:31:51,232 --> 00:31:54,414
said no to this feature, and even today we don't have it.

639
00:31:55,946 --> 00:31:58,987
One other thing that was asked a lot was the ability to,

640
00:31:59,408 --> 00:32:00,328
actually goes the other way,

641
00:32:00,648 --> 00:32:04,310
the ability to change the survivor third person perspective

642
00:32:04,490 --> 00:32:05,770
to go into first person,

643
00:32:06,190 --> 00:32:09,312
to have a better immersion and be more scared,

644
00:32:09,452 --> 00:32:10,492
basically as a survivor.

645
00:32:11,032 --> 00:32:12,493
And we've always pushed back

646
00:32:12,553 --> 00:32:15,614
because survivors are supposed to work as a team,

647
00:32:15,914 --> 00:32:17,515
and if you make your experience harder

648
00:32:17,555 --> 00:32:18,535
by going first person,

649
00:32:18,996 --> 00:32:22,197
you might make the other survivor experience kind of sucky.

650
00:32:23,017 --> 00:32:24,378
So we've decided not to go there.

651
00:32:26,495 --> 00:32:28,396
There are some small rules we broke, though,

652
00:32:29,056 --> 00:32:29,737
in the first month.

653
00:32:30,597 --> 00:32:32,078
Killer speed is an interesting one.

654
00:32:32,158 --> 00:32:33,418
When we developed the game,

655
00:32:33,438 --> 00:32:37,220
the chase economy,

656
00:32:37,960 --> 00:32:40,842
the speed of the killer and of the survivor

657
00:32:41,002 --> 00:32:43,083
was sacrosanct values

658
00:32:43,463 --> 00:32:45,484
that we decided that we would never change.

659
00:32:46,764 --> 00:32:49,285
But then the first killer that we released post-launch

660
00:32:50,206 --> 00:32:51,286
is our nurse.

661
00:32:51,606 --> 00:32:53,527
She teleports, she goes through wall.

662
00:32:54,405 --> 00:32:57,606
So we add to balance her by lowering her speed.

663
00:32:57,826 --> 00:33:00,227
So this is something we broke in the first month.

664
00:33:00,587 --> 00:33:03,849
Survive with friends, like I explained,

665
00:33:04,949 --> 00:33:06,610
in our vision, original vision,

666
00:33:07,230 --> 00:33:10,352
we wanted players to experience the game

667
00:33:10,832 --> 00:33:12,152
alone with strangers.

668
00:33:12,412 --> 00:33:15,794
This is like the uncertainty makes the game better that way.

669
00:33:16,134 --> 00:33:18,935
But, I mean, something that was requested a lot,

670
00:33:19,175 --> 00:33:20,416
so we decided to break that rule

671
00:33:20,436 --> 00:33:22,917
and let survivors play together with friends.

672
00:33:23,717 --> 00:33:25,798
And last one, last example, new killer powers.

673
00:33:26,318 --> 00:33:29,639
We were supposed, when we originally designed the game,

674
00:33:29,679 --> 00:33:31,719
that every killer that we would release post-launch

675
00:33:32,099 --> 00:33:35,040
was going to be stat change and little tweaks

676
00:33:35,740 --> 00:33:37,160
to create these new killers.

677
00:33:37,240 --> 00:33:39,221
So we start with a trapper and we change this

678
00:33:39,901 --> 00:33:41,601
a little bit, things here and there.

679
00:33:42,102 --> 00:33:44,642
But we decided to go another way,

680
00:33:44,662 --> 00:33:46,403
which is much better in my opinion,

681
00:33:46,763 --> 00:33:51,324
whereas we basically created complete new powers

682
00:33:51,704 --> 00:33:52,884
for these killers.

683
00:33:55,818 --> 00:33:57,579
So lesson here, be confident, not stubborn.

684
00:33:59,440 --> 00:34:01,161
I mean, it's fine changing your game.

685
00:34:01,241 --> 00:34:03,042
You still need to be true to your vision,

686
00:34:03,282 --> 00:34:06,784
but the community is gonna ask for something in your games

687
00:34:06,964 --> 00:34:08,865
and it's also fine to change it.

688
00:34:09,185 --> 00:34:10,186
It's gonna make something better.

689
00:34:12,987 --> 00:34:13,908
So there's two types of things

690
00:34:13,928 --> 00:34:15,208
that we do during live operation.

691
00:34:16,669 --> 00:34:17,430
Pretty basic stuff.

692
00:34:18,290 --> 00:34:21,912
We add new content and we do some services.

693
00:34:25,183 --> 00:34:26,964
So this is an example of a content drop

694
00:34:26,984 --> 00:34:28,025
that we do in Dead by Daylight.

695
00:34:28,505 --> 00:34:29,526
We call them chapters.

696
00:34:30,006 --> 00:34:33,128
It's a format that we use that is always the same.

697
00:34:33,568 --> 00:34:35,289
So when we release a content drop,

698
00:34:35,329 --> 00:34:37,730
we have a killer, we have a survivor,

699
00:34:38,110 --> 00:34:40,512
and we have a new map that's accessible to everyone.

700
00:34:41,192 --> 00:34:42,333
Survivor comes with new perks,

701
00:34:42,793 --> 00:34:44,334
and the killer is the most important of all,

702
00:34:44,594 --> 00:34:48,236
comes with new fiction, a new lore,

703
00:34:49,617 --> 00:34:54,119
and a new power that redefines the gameplay of the game.

704
00:34:57,676 --> 00:34:58,817
So, here are some examples.

705
00:35:00,058 --> 00:35:01,660
When we create these new characters,

706
00:35:01,680 --> 00:35:03,602
we really try to break the game in a good way.

707
00:35:04,203 --> 00:35:08,027
So, the nurse teleports, changes the chase completely,

708
00:35:08,407 --> 00:35:09,769
so breaks the game in a good way.

709
00:35:10,089 --> 00:35:10,770
Really interesting.

710
00:35:11,551 --> 00:35:12,472
Players need to adapt.

711
00:35:12,912 --> 00:35:16,196
The Entryist, which released one year after the launch.

712
00:35:17,215 --> 00:35:18,816
is our first character with a range attack.

713
00:35:18,837 --> 00:35:20,938
So again, changes the dynamic completely

714
00:35:21,078 --> 00:35:23,361
because all of the others would have normal melee.

715
00:35:24,542 --> 00:35:26,603
So again, need to adapt to this new gameplay.

716
00:35:27,504 --> 00:35:29,846
The pig, which is the last killer we released,

717
00:35:30,667 --> 00:35:33,329
adds a new objective to the survivor completely.

718
00:35:33,469 --> 00:35:35,812
So she adds a reverse bear trap.

719
00:35:35,932 --> 00:35:37,493
So she's from the Saw franchise.

720
00:35:38,394 --> 00:35:41,396
She adds the reverse bear trap on the head of the survivor.

721
00:35:41,959 --> 00:35:46,902
and they can't escape even though they repaired the five generators

722
00:35:46,942 --> 00:35:48,443
and they have the exit gate open.

723
00:35:48,723 --> 00:35:51,445
They have to find the jigsaw box and find the correct key

724
00:35:51,485 --> 00:35:53,146
to get this thing off their head.

725
00:35:53,526 --> 00:35:56,808
So it adds a new core loop to the experience.

726
00:35:57,769 --> 00:36:01,131
So again, need to adapt drastically to this new character.

727
00:36:02,715 --> 00:36:05,040
So what is cool about having a format like that

728
00:36:05,801 --> 00:36:09,408
is that it creates a solid pipeline for your team.

729
00:36:09,789 --> 00:36:11,172
So having the same kind of format

730
00:36:11,232 --> 00:36:13,417
every time you create a DLC, the team.

731
00:36:14,954 --> 00:36:17,597
knows exactly what they have to do and what to expect.

732
00:36:18,277 --> 00:36:20,659
It is also very clear for players.

733
00:36:20,939 --> 00:36:21,960
When we announce a chapter,

734
00:36:21,980 --> 00:36:23,822
they know exactly what is going to be in there.

735
00:36:25,143 --> 00:36:27,585
And it adds to, well, everyone experience.

736
00:36:27,625 --> 00:36:31,348
In our case, adding a new killer with new gameplay

737
00:36:31,549 --> 00:36:34,271
means that you can play this killer

738
00:36:34,311 --> 00:36:35,212
and have a new experience,

739
00:36:35,732 --> 00:36:37,574
but you can also, as a survivor,

740
00:36:37,694 --> 00:36:39,075
encounter this new character.

741
00:36:39,115 --> 00:36:41,898
So it's like we're adding a new boss fight to the game.

742
00:36:45,637 --> 00:36:48,379
Limitations though, redefining the whole gameplay

743
00:36:48,419 --> 00:36:52,121
every time we do a content drop is difficult for a small team.

744
00:36:52,582 --> 00:36:54,983
It takes a lot of dedication and bandwidth,

745
00:36:55,344 --> 00:36:57,285
so it takes away a little bit of focus

746
00:36:57,385 --> 00:36:59,246
of supporting what's already in the game.

747
00:37:00,087 --> 00:37:03,028
It adds complexity to the players.

748
00:37:03,449 --> 00:37:05,750
We're actually reaching critical mass at the moment.

749
00:37:06,130 --> 00:37:08,772
By adding all of these new gameplay components

750
00:37:08,872 --> 00:37:10,533
every time we release a killer, it

751
00:37:10,773 --> 00:37:14,216
deepens the gap between veterans and new players.

752
00:37:14,836 --> 00:37:18,980
So to fight this problem, we just have to do a lot more

753
00:37:19,120 --> 00:37:21,583
on-boarding about these characters, add more ints,

754
00:37:21,863 --> 00:37:25,186
and teach our players these new gameplays

755
00:37:25,386 --> 00:37:27,188
so that they don't get confused.

756
00:37:30,271 --> 00:37:30,872
Now, services.

757
00:37:31,552 --> 00:37:36,477
So this is the first year of all the updates we did.

758
00:37:37,580 --> 00:37:39,121
There's a lot of stuff, a lot of service.

759
00:37:39,361 --> 00:37:41,262
So service, just so that we're on the same page,

760
00:37:41,802 --> 00:37:44,864
there are free updates, just make the game better.

761
00:37:44,884 --> 00:37:49,126
And I just wanted to go quickly over some of the ones

762
00:37:49,146 --> 00:37:49,966
that served us better.

763
00:37:49,986 --> 00:37:52,187
It's good to put names on them.

764
00:37:54,248 --> 00:37:54,849
Base features.

765
00:37:56,329 --> 00:37:59,051
So we had to cut a lot of things

766
00:37:59,151 --> 00:38:00,491
to focus on the core of the game,

767
00:38:00,811 --> 00:38:02,052
so that it would be solid.

768
00:38:04,264 --> 00:38:06,706
Releasing a game on PC, there's obviously things

769
00:38:06,726 --> 00:38:08,909
that the player will expect day one.

770
00:38:09,369 --> 00:38:13,493
In our case, for example, we didn't have remapping.

771
00:38:13,733 --> 00:38:15,174
We couldn't customize the control.

772
00:38:15,194 --> 00:38:18,237
This is something that players expected day one.

773
00:38:18,638 --> 00:38:20,299
So these services are really nice.

774
00:38:20,319 --> 00:38:21,700
You should do them early as possible.

