00:41:27,358 --> 00:41:29,839
So, balancing a game is difficult.

838
00:41:31,012 --> 00:41:33,792
I think we can all agree, balancing an asymmetrical

839
00:41:33,832 --> 00:41:36,193
multiplayer is really difficult.

840
00:41:37,833 --> 00:41:41,314
And I really wanted to go quickly how or what we use

841
00:41:41,674 --> 00:41:42,835
to balance the game.

842
00:41:43,795 --> 00:41:48,596
So we use three sources, gut instincts, data analytics,

843
00:41:49,056 --> 00:41:50,097
and community feedback.

844
00:41:51,437 --> 00:41:52,437
All important.

845
00:41:55,518 --> 00:41:58,179
Quick note about gut instincts, when you're creating

846
00:41:58,219 --> 00:41:59,599
something new, we're, I mean.

847
00:42:00,694 --> 00:42:03,896
We had no clue doing the symmetrical multiplayer horror game.

848
00:42:04,536 --> 00:42:07,437
Doing new characters, that changes the game completely.

849
00:42:09,098 --> 00:42:12,740
Working in design, you don't have players,

850
00:42:12,760 --> 00:42:14,921
you don't have analytics, you don't have anything to use.

851
00:42:15,161 --> 00:42:17,942
So you know your game, your team knows the game,

852
00:42:17,982 --> 00:42:21,064
so a team debate and going with your instinct

853
00:42:21,224 --> 00:42:22,965
is the normal way to go at that point.

854
00:42:25,584 --> 00:42:30,687
Data analytics is really interesting for us, for the team.

855
00:42:30,748 --> 00:42:34,450
It was the first project where we actually used analytics.

856
00:42:36,151 --> 00:42:38,673
One of the best addition, that's Julien by the way.

857
00:42:39,293 --> 00:42:41,895
Hello, hello Julien, you can say hi.

858
00:42:41,955 --> 00:42:45,057
He's a really fun guy, a data analyst

859
00:42:46,398 --> 00:42:49,080
that we added to the game, to the project, sorry.

860
00:42:50,160 --> 00:42:52,742
He's a PhD evolutionary biology.

861
00:42:53,002 --> 00:42:54,443
So this guy is.

862
00:42:55,364 --> 00:42:58,566
awesome addition, E will crunch through our data,

863
00:42:59,046 --> 00:43:02,808
but also can make link to the psychology of our players.

864
00:43:03,269 --> 00:43:06,791
So E works with our designer to find

865
00:43:07,211 --> 00:43:10,633
what we can change in the feature or what we can balance to

866
00:43:10,653 --> 00:43:14,236
address some specific personality-based

867
00:43:15,216 --> 00:43:15,516
problem.

868
00:43:18,015 --> 00:43:19,936
Data analytic is not optional.

869
00:43:20,537 --> 00:43:22,458
Now we make sure that everything we design,

870
00:43:22,518 --> 00:43:25,721
everything we add, it's a part of the scope.

871
00:43:26,121 --> 00:43:28,523
We think about what we'll need as analytics

872
00:43:29,304 --> 00:43:31,586
and it's always thought in the future.

873
00:43:33,888 --> 00:43:34,789
Be mindful of the hooks.

874
00:43:35,950 --> 00:43:41,074
When we, before release, we weren't sure

875
00:43:41,094 --> 00:43:44,637
what we needed as hooks into analytics.

876
00:43:45,177 --> 00:43:45,838
So we've added.

877
00:43:46,493 --> 00:43:48,835
hooks everywhere, analytics about everything.

878
00:43:49,435 --> 00:43:51,096
And this is a problem, it's something that you won't

879
00:43:51,136 --> 00:43:51,857
be able to use.

880
00:43:52,057 --> 00:43:54,558
If you get data about everything, it's gonna bloat

881
00:43:54,738 --> 00:43:58,781
your data, it will be super expensive, and you won't

882
00:43:58,821 --> 00:44:00,242
be able to analyze this data.

883
00:44:00,302 --> 00:44:04,464
We had to scrap most of it, actually, and make it lighter.

884
00:44:05,685 --> 00:44:09,588
So, not enough is a problem, too much is also a problem.

885
00:44:09,808 --> 00:44:12,970
You just need to design and be mindful of what you need.

886
00:44:14,674 --> 00:44:16,955
And the last point, data versus perception,

887
00:44:17,015 --> 00:44:17,835
is really important.

888
00:44:17,855 --> 00:44:19,877
Data analytics is really strong,

889
00:44:19,937 --> 00:44:22,999
but when the community thinks that there's a problem,

890
00:44:23,179 --> 00:44:26,661
it doesn't matter how strong is your data.

891
00:44:26,681 --> 00:44:28,242
They won't believe you.

892
00:44:28,542 --> 00:44:31,404
Like, the perception is much stronger.

893
00:44:31,424 --> 00:44:33,545
And that's why it can't be the only tool

894
00:44:33,565 --> 00:44:34,686
you use to balance the game.

895
00:44:35,946 --> 00:44:37,027
So another tool that we use.

896
00:44:37,855 --> 00:44:39,016
is a Discord group.

897
00:44:39,296 --> 00:44:42,477
So we formed that last year with an elite group

898
00:44:42,877 --> 00:44:44,458
of our players.

899
00:44:45,278 --> 00:44:47,779
So we found players that had more than 1,000 hours

900
00:44:47,839 --> 00:44:49,419
in the game, that were really invested,

901
00:44:49,439 --> 00:44:51,580
that could play the game really well,

902
00:44:51,880 --> 00:44:55,041
and that add constructive feedback about these features.

903
00:44:55,481 --> 00:44:57,862
And we invited them into the Discord group

904
00:44:57,902 --> 00:44:59,723
where our designers, some engineers.

905
00:45:00,273 --> 00:45:02,935
and community manager interact with them directly.

906
00:45:03,335 --> 00:45:05,597
We actually talk with them pretty much every day

907
00:45:05,757 --> 00:45:08,879
to talk about a balance path that we want to do,

908
00:45:08,999 --> 00:45:10,940
a new feature, to get their feedback.

909
00:45:11,321 --> 00:45:14,243
They really represent the community

910
00:45:14,283 --> 00:45:15,283
and what the community thinks.

911
00:45:16,064 --> 00:45:18,185
They're also under NDA, so it's possible for us

912
00:45:18,225 --> 00:45:20,507
to create specific builds just for them,

913
00:45:20,687 --> 00:45:21,588
and we can play with them.

914
00:45:22,208 --> 00:45:25,610
And they are so invested in the game

915
00:45:25,650 --> 00:45:29,153
that they're much better than anyone in the team.

916
00:45:29,606 --> 00:45:31,626
so their feedback is super valuable.

917
00:45:34,387 --> 00:45:37,468
So just Trulison learned about balance.

918
00:45:38,348 --> 00:45:40,308
First of all, don't react to first reactions.

919
00:45:41,409 --> 00:45:43,729
We found out that every time we release new content,

920
00:45:44,229 --> 00:45:47,210
it takes at least two weeks for the players to adapt.

921
00:45:47,950 --> 00:45:50,091
The data analytics that you receive

922
00:45:50,111 --> 00:45:52,351
in these first two weeks is rubbish, you can't use it,

923
00:45:52,811 --> 00:45:56,312
and their reaction is also not real.

924
00:45:56,472 --> 00:45:57,672
They need that time to adapt

925
00:45:57,752 --> 00:45:59,433
and understand what has changed in the game.

926
00:46:00,507 --> 00:46:01,448
Leave no one behind.

927
00:46:01,808 --> 00:46:07,093
When we do a balance pass for a problem that is for the

928
00:46:07,113 --> 00:46:10,156
higher ranks, for example, we always need to make sure that

929
00:46:10,356 --> 00:46:12,598
this change will not affect in a bad way the

930
00:46:12,638 --> 00:46:13,759
lower ranks players.

931
00:46:14,659 --> 00:46:15,740
So we need to be inclusive.

932
00:46:17,022 --> 00:46:17,882
And communicate a lot.

933
00:46:18,203 --> 00:46:20,965
When we do changes like that, we usually communicate before

934
00:46:21,005 --> 00:46:23,147
we do the change to get the feedback.

935
00:46:24,220 --> 00:46:26,461
We communicate when we do the patch,

936
00:46:26,782 --> 00:46:28,463
and we communicate a lot afterwards

937
00:46:28,563 --> 00:46:30,504
to make sure that there's no wrong interpretation

938
00:46:30,644 --> 00:46:31,365
of the changes.

939
00:46:34,367 --> 00:46:35,147
Right, so patches.

940
00:46:36,989 --> 00:46:37,589
Last segment.

941
00:46:37,949 --> 00:46:41,191
So, obviously, if you're gonna do a lot of services

942
00:46:42,172 --> 00:46:43,033
and a lot of the content,

943
00:46:43,293 --> 00:46:44,854
you're gonna do a lot of patches.

944
00:46:45,514 --> 00:46:49,717
And we have a crazy cadence where we would do patches

945
00:46:49,757 --> 00:46:51,979
and not fix every two weeks about.

946
00:46:52,639 --> 00:46:55,681
So, we did about five million, give or take,

947
00:46:56,121 --> 00:46:58,502
different patches, and I think that we did

948
00:46:58,742 --> 00:47:02,044
all the mistakes possible when doing patches.

949
00:47:02,644 --> 00:47:05,906
So, I prepared a blitz of different mistakes,

950
00:47:06,286 --> 00:47:07,587
so we'll go quickly through them.

951
00:47:09,128 --> 00:47:11,309
Huge patch to download with no player-facing changes.

952
00:47:12,369 --> 00:47:13,810
Patches are too far apart.

953
00:47:14,511 --> 00:47:15,851
Patches are too close together.

954
00:47:16,872 --> 00:47:18,293
IPing a patch that never comes.

955
00:47:19,283 --> 00:47:20,804
Iping a patch that doesn't deliver.

956
00:47:21,645 --> 00:47:23,526
Forget to communicate about an awesome patch.

957
00:47:23,706 --> 00:47:24,527
Nobody knows about it.

958
00:47:25,168 --> 00:47:26,669
Patching without patch notes.

959
00:47:27,910 --> 00:47:30,031
Leaving space to interpretation in the patch notes.

960
00:47:30,652 --> 00:47:32,774
Forgetting to mention the change in the patch notes.

961
00:47:33,694 --> 00:47:35,556
Forgetting to remove the mention of a change

962
00:47:35,576 --> 00:47:37,037
that was reverted in the patch notes.

963
00:47:38,058 --> 00:47:41,000
Patching on a Friday because of limited support

964
00:47:41,040 --> 00:47:43,222
during the weekend, that's bad, you know about that one.

965
00:47:43,963 --> 00:47:46,064
Patching on a Thursday because one day is not enough.

966
00:47:46,999 --> 00:47:49,340
Patching on a Wednesday because two days is not enough.

967
00:47:50,481 --> 00:47:52,562
Patching on a Thursday because the last four patches

968
00:47:52,602 --> 00:47:54,843
were awesome and surely this one will be too.

969
00:47:54,863 --> 00:47:56,424
Horrible mistake.

970
00:47:57,325 --> 00:48:00,747
Patching just before the holidays against limited support.

971
00:48:02,087 --> 00:48:03,688
Patching because it's time.

972
00:48:04,583 --> 00:48:04,963
Horrible.

973
00:48:05,723 --> 00:48:08,505
Patching a bug fix which heavily impacts the game balance.

974
00:48:09,485 --> 00:48:10,986
Patching a balance pass on a character

975
00:48:11,006 --> 00:48:12,247
that released yesterday.

976
00:48:13,327 --> 00:48:14,488
Nah, that can't happen.

977
00:48:15,188 --> 00:48:17,229
Patching with data we don't want to reveal just yet,

978
00:48:17,469 --> 00:48:18,490
so we did a couple of leaks.

979
00:48:19,430 --> 00:48:21,731
Patching PC way before patching on console,

980
00:48:22,072 --> 00:48:23,132
they're gonna be mad about it.

981
00:48:23,652 --> 00:48:26,514
And patching console one hour before patching on PC.

982
00:48:26,714 --> 00:48:28,295
They're gonna be super pissed about it.

983
00:48:30,216 --> 00:48:32,057
So some best practices, I don't want to go through

984
00:48:32,097 --> 00:48:34,019
all of them, but some important ones,

985
00:48:34,059 --> 00:48:36,841
if this wasn't clear enough, patch early in the week

986
00:48:37,381 --> 00:48:38,362
so that you can outfix.

987
00:48:39,663 --> 00:48:40,864
Have an emergency plan.

988
00:48:41,084 --> 00:48:44,686
So we put a pipeline for this, which is great.

989
00:48:44,766 --> 00:48:47,428
So if something happens during a weekend or an evening,

990
00:48:48,029 --> 00:48:50,851
the team members can know who to contact

991
00:48:50,871 --> 00:48:52,912
so that the problem is fixed as soon as possible.

992
00:48:54,525 --> 00:48:57,526
And PTB, so public test build, super easy on Steam.

993
00:48:58,186 --> 00:49:03,267
Whenever possible, you can create this specific build,

994
00:49:03,547 --> 00:49:05,948
give to the player before it's actually released.

995
00:49:06,328 --> 00:49:08,348
They will test it, they will be able to comment.

996
00:49:08,488 --> 00:49:10,769
If you have the analytics in there, it's super useful

997
00:49:10,829 --> 00:49:12,649
to see if your patch is gonna be okay.

998
00:49:13,049 --> 00:49:14,589
And you can even do a survey to make sure

